## 1. Selected Storage System and Dataset\
\
We are using **MongoDB** as the storage system and the provided **AirBnB dataset** as the target dataset (Los Angeles, Portland, Salem, and San Diego). The dataset has four core files per city: `listings`, `calendar`, `reviews`, and `neighbourhoods`.\
\
For this milestone, the assignment asks for design completeness plus proof that at least some items are loaded. So we designed for the full four-city scope, and loaded a representative subset for proof-of-concept validation.\
\
## 2. Data Representation in MongoDB\
\
### 2.1 Final representation\
\
We model the dataset as four collections so that each source file maps cleanly into its own write path:\
\
1. `listings`\
2. `calendar`\
3. `reviews`\
4. `neighborhoods`\
\
The key design decision is to keep high-volume time-series data (`calendar`, `reviews`) out of listing documents. It is tempting to embed everything, but that would create very large listing documents and expensive rewrites when availability/reviews update. Keeping these as separate collections gives us better write behavior and clearer index control.\
\
Example document shapes:\
\
```javascript\
// listings\
\{\
  city: "portland",\
  listing_id: 37676,\
  name: "Mt. Hood View in the Pearl District",\
  neighborhood: "Pearl",\
  room_type: "Entire home/apt",\
  accommodates: 4,\
  property_type: "Apartment",\
  amenities_raw: "\{TV,Wifi,...\}",\
  price: 125,\
  review_scores_rating: 94,\
  host_id: 162158,\
  host_name: "Paul",\
  listing_url: "https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/37676",\
  description: "..."\
\}\
\
// calendar\
\{\
  city: "salem",\
  listing_id: 199568,\
  date: "2025-12-30",\
  available: false,\
  price: 89,\
  adjusted_price: 89,\
  minimum_nights: 4,\
  maximum_nights: 120\
\}\
\
// reviews\
\{\
  city: "san_diego",\
  listing_id: 123456,\
  review_id: 987654321,\
  date: "2024-12-14",\
  reviewer_id: 45200,\
  reviewer_name: "Alice",\
  comments: "Great place..."\
\}\
\
// neighborhoods\
\{\
  city: "los_angeles",\
  neighborhood: "Hollywood"\
\}\
```\
\
### 2.2 Indexes\
\
Indexes are chosen directly from query patterns in the assignment:\
\
```javascript\
db.listings.createIndex(\{ city: 1, listing_id: 1 \}, \{ unique: true \})\
db.listings.createIndex(\{ city: 1, neighborhood: 1, room_type: 1 \})\
db.listings.createIndex(\{ host_id: 1, city: 1 \})\
\
db.calendar.createIndex(\{ city: 1, listing_id: 1, date: 1 \})\
db.calendar.createIndex(\{ city: 1, date: 1, available: 1 \})\
\
db.reviews.createIndex(\{ city: 1, listing_id: 1, date: 1 \})\
db.reviews.createIndex(\{ reviewer_id: 1, listing_id: 1, date: 1 \})\
\
db.neighborhoods.createIndex(\{ city: 1, neighborhood: 1 \}, \{ unique: true \})\
```\
\
Why these are preferred:\
- most query filters begin with city and listing id;\
- availability and monthly trend queries are date-heavy, so date prefixes matter;\
- query 6 needs reviewer/listing history checks, so reviewer-based index support is important.\
\
### 2.3 Alternative representation considered\
\
We also considered a denormalized model where each `listings` document embeds:\
- a large `calendar` array of daily availability entries, and\
- a `reviews` subdocument array.\
\
That alternative can make some listing-centric reads simpler (single-document fetch), but it is weaker for this assignment because:\
- `calendar` is large and update-heavy; embedded arrays can push document size and rewrite costs;\
- monthly and city-wide analytics become array-unwind heavy;\
- index flexibility is reduced compared to separate collections with targeted compound indexes.\
\
So the final design keeps `calendar` and `reviews` external, and uses indexed joins (`$lookup`) only when needed.\
\
## 3. Data Restructuring, Cleaning, and Loading Plan\
\
### 3.1 Restructuring and cleaning\
\
The source files are CSV/CSV.GZ and include mixed formatting. Before loading:\
\
1. Normalize city labels to canonical keys (`los_angeles`, `portland`, `salem`, `san_diego`).\
2. Convert numeric fields:\
   - `price`, `adjusted_price` from currency strings to numeric\
   - `minimum_nights`, `maximum_nights`, `accommodates`, IDs to integers\
3. Convert availability flag:\
   - `t/f` to boolean\
4. Parse and preserve dates as ISO-like strings first; convert to `Date` at load/query time if needed for strict date arithmetic.\
5. Keep only fields required by current and expected queries to reduce write and storage overhead.\
6. Drop/flag malformed records (missing listing id, malformed date, invalid city).\
\
